l milieus and modes of living. While modernism was publicized as a fusion of technology, new materials, and rational aesthetics to improve the lives of ordinary people, it was often out of reach to the very masses it purportedly served. Schuldenfrei exposes the disconnect between modernism's utopian discourse and its luxury objects and elite architectural commissions. Despite the movement's egalitarian rhetoric, many modern designs addressed the desires of the privileged individual. Yet as Schuldenfrei demonstrates, luxury was integral not only to how modern buildings and objects were designed, manufactured, and sold, but has contributed to modernism's appeal to this day.Featuring stunning color images throughout, Luxury and Modernism provides an entirely new look at one of the most celebrated and influential eras in the history of architecture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Sep 2021) 0aDesignzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aLuxury. 0aModern movement (Architecture)zGermany. 0aModernism (Aesthetics)zGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aTechnologyxSocial aspectszGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 7aARCHITECTURE / History / Modern (late 19th Century to 1945).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060659140uhttps://doi.org/10.23943/9781400890484zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400890484423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781400890484/original  a978-3-11-060659-1  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK